<div id="review_3473010162" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3473010162" />
    <a title="Luís" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/117399210-lu-s"><img alt="Luís" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1620236159p2/117399210.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3473010162?book_show_action=true">Aug 01, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Luís" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Luís" href="/user/show/117399210-lu-s">Luís</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9788440704535" href="/book/show/25339415-o-pr-ncipe-e-o-pobre">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/117399210-lu-s?shelf=classics">classics</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/117399210-lu-s?shelf=historical-fiction">historical-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/117399210-lu-s?shelf=favorites">favorites</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/117399210-lu-s?shelf=adventure">adventure</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/117399210-lu-s?shelf=usa-and-canada">usa-and-canada</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/117399210-lu-s?shelf=children">children</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3473010162" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17670418044280290147">The prince and the pauper is a lucidly written masterpiece by Mark Twain. Easily understandable, the book is a display of sheer genius. All the characters have thoroughly explained, and as you go along, you fall in love with most of them, especially the prince and the Knight Miles Hendon. The former is a personification of pampered innocence while the latter is an epitome of self-less generosity. The story doesn&apos;t take long to shift gears, and as soon as the two protagonists move places (by mist</span>
  <span id="freeText17670418044280290147" style="display:none">The prince and the pauper is a lucidly written masterpiece by Mark Twain. Easily understandable, the book is a display of sheer genius. All the characters have thoroughly explained, and as you go along, you fall in love with most of them, especially the prince and the Knight Miles Hendon. The former is a personification of pampered innocence while the latter is an epitome of self-less generosity. The story doesn't take long to shift gears, and as soon as the two protagonists move places (by mistake, of course), things start to get interesting. The author succeeds in raising antipathy towards some characters, especially the head of the Canty family (Pauper's family). The characters are so black and white that even children can comprehend the book with minimal effort. <br />The book also tastes success in creating the milieu of the era. The concept of the whipping boy is queer yet believable. For trivia, whipping boy is a person in the kingdom who takes the punishment on behalf of the prince if the latter is not doing well in studies. Teachers, afraid of hitting the would-be King, beat the whipping boy and his earnings are comparable to the whipping he gets. <br />The end again is pleased, despite the death of the King. Despite the trials and tribulations, the young prince goes through. One consistently gets the feeling that it is only for the time being, and everything will change for good. This fact makes it even more loveable. The apprehensions of the pauper in the kingdom have also captured well. <br />All in all, this is a good read for those looking for a change from the run-of-the-mill preaching fictions. The story has plainly stated, and it is up to the reader to extract morals. No explicit attempt has made to do the same. </span>
  <a data-text-id="17670418044280290147" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


